animal.description:
Alfred is a very nice Miniature Schnauzer.  He is five years old, weighs about 21 pounds, is salt and pepper in color and has natural ears and tail.  He LOVES to play ball and playing with his toys.  He also loves being in your lap and in the big bed, if he is allowed.  He is kennel trained, but will give you those sad eyes if he has to go in.  He is also doggie door trained and will sit to receive his food.  Overall, he is really a good, friendly dog.  His only issue is if he meets new people and they reach to pet him, he might nip them.  He needs to meet people slowly.  At his foster home after the 2nd day there, he realized he could trust them and was very friendly.  He would not do well with children and needs an experienced Schnauzer owner.
Contact Miniature Schnauzer Rescue of Houston at msrh.org and complete the Adoption Application.
Adoption Fee:  $350

animal.description:
Our big, happy boy Garth is searching for his furever family! If you are looking for a big, loving, happy-go-lucky furball to be your companion, Garth may be the pyrfect boy for you. Garth came to us as a stray with unknown history, but he has quickly won over the hearts of our volunteers with his happy, wiggly butt and a tail that never stops wagging. This boy simply thrives with the love and attention of people - as long as he can be in the proximity of his people, he is as happy as can be. Still very much an oversized puppy, Garth loves playing with his toys and/or foster siblings for short bursts, then he promptly finds a cozy place to plop down for a nice long nap to recharge. How cute is that? These days, Garth is working on getting used to being around new people (he was a stray, after all) and learning that a leash can lead to many good things. This big boy still has a lot to learn in life, but he has such a happy, positive, eager-to-please attitude that training is not a chore to him. In fact, he will most definitely benefit with consistent, positive reinforcement training. If you are willing to open your heart and your home to this wonderfully sweet boy, he will no doubt be on his best behavior and mature into your most loyal companion for life!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description: Hi, my name is Dawson and the nice people from BDRR rescued me from an over-crowded South Carolina animal shelter. I am sweet guy and known to be talkative with loads of personality. I am good with other dogs and love my humans too. I'm a little mouthy and can play a little rough, so best if I go to a home without small children. I would love to go to obedience training with you so I can learn how to be the best canine citizen. Unfortunately my previous owner did not have me on monthly heart worm preventative and now I have tested positive for heart worms. Heart worms can be deadly to us pups if left untreated so of course the nice people at BDRR will treat me with a special heart worm treatment plan to make me healthy again. The adoption team can explain the whole treatment process and also talk to you about the importance of keeping me on heart worm preventative going forward.

animal.description:
Gibson aka Grover von Gefell is a wonderful 3-4 year old Shepherd mix. This handsome, bicolor boy can be so sweet with the people he knows at the rescue but is on the shy side (including a bit hand shy) with strangers. That is why he is seeking an adults-only calmer home. Gibson is a medium energy dog and is a very curious boy. On his walks, he keeps an eye out ahead and will lead if you let him. If you too like a quick pace to your adventures out, he is happy to join you on a good jog. Gibson is a smart boy; he knows several commands and is eager to learn more. He has experience being in a home, is housebroken, and has shown good indoor and outside manners. Gibson does well around other dogs, whether on leash or off. As is his demeanor, he says hello but then settles back and does his own thing. (No cats please.) Gibson is seeking a kind home with people that will give him time, and who will appreciate his sensitivity and loyalty.

Location: New Orleans, Louisiana 

Nala was apart of a creuilty case in North Louisiana. They were holding her at the shelter since she was 3 months old while the case was ongoing in court. 
 Nala is approximately 10 months old, up to date on vaccinations, spayed & microchipped. 

Since Nala has spent almost her entire life living at a shelter she is very puppy like. She knows nothing but a cement kennel with limited human interaction. Through no fault of her own, this 10 month old girl has the mind set of a 3 month old puppy, wanting to play and eager to learn new things. She is an amazing girl with so much love to give. 

Nala is house trained, kennel trained & knows his basic commands/manners.

Interested adopters can fill out an application at canehavenrescue.com. 
Any possible questions about Nala, please email canehavenrescue@gmail.com 

Cane Haven Rescue will transport any of their adoptable dogs to the right home. We do require adoption fees that are based on the age & health status of the adoptable dog. The adoption fee covers every single dog in CHR with vaccinations, heartworm test, deworming, microchip, spay/neuter & medications. All CHR adoptable dogs are current on their monthly  heartworm and flea medication. A CHR representative will do a home check to ensure the pets are placed in a secure and loving home. 

www.canehavenrescue.com

animal.description:
Butterscotch is a a 3-year old, 47lb, energetic pittie mix looking for her fur-ever home! She was rescued from Mexico and since being in the states, has been vaccinated, microchipped, and enrolled in training classes. Butterscotch aims to please and just wants to be close to you. She enjoys her time in the backyard and likes to go on walks, but she is also just as happy laying in her bed next to you or splooting on the floor. Butterscotch did not have an easy life before coming to us so she needs a family that is willing to be patient with her. She currently lives with our 6 resident dogs and has done amazingly well with all of them. She did have a squabble with one of her rescue mates, so while she is dog friendly to our dogs, she doesnt get along with one dog in our home.... With that said, she would need to meet any future fur sibling to see if it would work out or not. Butterscotch is not a fan of cats and has not lived with children but given her size, and energy level, I think she would do best with older children. Butterscotch has made so much progress in the past few weeks and now will be the perfect addition to someone's home!

*Applications to adopt: wwwTucsonColdWetNoses.com Home Visit / ID and Residence Verification is required. Compliance does not imply or guarantee adoption. Approval is the sole discretion of CWN representative(s).

T ori is great with all her foster siblings from the smallest to the biggest. She follows behind her brothers and plays chase in the yard, or hide and seek in the house. Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

Bruno is a beagle mix approximately 5 years old.

He is neutered up to date on his vaccinations and microchipped. He weighs approximately 25 lb . He is a special needs boy. He has anxiety about meeting strangers. His perfect home would be, a quiet mature home, with a secure fenced yard, not a lot of socializing with company, a smaller buddy preferably female, and a new momma. Men scare him. His reaction to strangers is to bark. And keep barking til the scarey things go away. The best part of Bruno is that once he is settled in he is a total lovebug. He doesn't just snuggle with you, he is velcro. He looks at you with loving eyes and just wants to be by you. He's extremely strong and quick. He likes to bolt out the door instead of just walking out. He's a unique little guy and is looking for a new mama that will accept him just the way he is.

If you're interested in Bruno please contact Alternative Humane Society.

He's happy and loves to play outside. He is a Barker! No apartments or condos sorry.

If you're interested in Bruno and would like to meet him contact Alternative Humane Society by filling out a statement of interest.

Opal is a very sweet 2.5 year old girl who would like nothing more than be by your side. She is good with people of all genders and size. During the COVID-19 outbreak, Opal has kept her foster mom company while she works from home, and is very loving and eager to please. One of her favorite activities is going on car rides. Opal suffers from Ovarian Remnant Syndrome and, although she has been spayed, she goes into heat twice a year. When Opal goes into her next heat cycle, Shenandoah Shepherd Rescue will coordinate and pay for Opal's exploratory surgery to attempt to find the remaining tissue and correct the problem; however, sometimes surgery is not always successful.

Good with Adults, Good with Kids, Does Good in the Car, Not Good with Dogs, Not Good with Cats, Somewhat vocal, Housebroken, Cratetrained, Leashtrained, Affectionate
If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
Bowie is a 2 year old neutered male flat coat retriever with potential border collie in the mix.  He has white markings such as the razor thin blaze down his nose and along his throat; white tips on his two hind paws and a touch of white on two of his front paw toes.  His  expressive amber eyes add to his intelligent character.

The absolute best household dynamic for Bowie is a quiet, easy going ADULT household with few surprises day to day.  The adults should be experienced large dog owners that are easy going, relaxed, consistent  and know how to set clear, fair boundaries and follow a formula for continued success.  Tight living situations in close community type neighborhoods and reliance on street walking are NOT for this dog.  He'd be at his personal best in a more spacious rural scenario where he can just be a relaxed companion to those he loves and where there are limited influences to challenge his behavior.

At just 6 weeks of life Bowie was taken from his mom and shipped to NJ and irresponsibly placed by his rescue organization.  He lived with five children under the age of eight.  Socialization of the dog was not a priority and now 2 years later he's way behind in  learning the way we all learn - by cataloging new experiences and building our self-confidence and awareness of a bigger world. 

Bowie is a sensitive soul - much like a nature lover or artist that prefers quiet times in open spaces and interacting with the people he trusts and loves.  

  I asked my husband to describe Bowie and he said he's a fantastic  dog with one quirk and that quirk is random apprehension towards NEW experiences.  The key to success with this dog is taking new experiences (for him) slowly, very slowly.  This is a dog that requires a management protocol - he can't be thrown into situations with a lets see what happens approach.  He needs to bond with his caretakers that believe in him and that will have time/patience to help him build confidence in his surroundings. He's what I call a TRUE RESCUE - a work in progress that will be extremely rewarding to his caretaker over time.

To discuss Bowie please send an e:mail summarizing your household dynamic.  auntmarysdoghouse@yahoo.com. You can also leave a VM message on 908-362-1333 but e:mail get s a quicker response. Thank you!

animal.description:
The highlights....3 year old beagle/basset hound mix, 41 pounds, great with dogs, crate trained, housebroken in his foster home.  Super sweet with people.  One of the two founding members of The Beagle Brothers.  (please see Coltrane's listing on our site...just in case you're looking for double trouble!)

REQUIRED: fenced yard; another playful dog in the home (or maybe adopt his brother Coltrane too?); experience with the problem-solving,  creativity and patience  needed with hound-style hounds and their "we do things our own way" approach to life; significant distance from your neighbors as a sound buffer; a household free of young and fairly young children (due to how much awareness and organization it takes to keep a nosey and busy hound from getting into vet-requiring trouble with discarded toys and their tiny pieces,  half-finished and left-behind lunches and snacks, etc. )

More detail...Elvis is one of the two sniff-iest, snort-iest, snuffle-iest hounds we've met yet. (Coltrane is the other!) This guy experiences pure joy while tracking...multiple times per day...for prolonged periods of time.  He frequently sings the Song of His Hound Dog People...loudly...while tracking. (Insert consideration of your proximity to your neighbors here...no apartments, town homes, duplexes, or homes without very large yards).  Elvis loves other dogs, affection from his humans, and squishy dog beds.   He has settled into a routine well after coming from an outdoor life with no rules or training.  That said, he is used to spending a great deal of the day exploring a fenced yard, wrestling with another dog, and checking in with humans for affection. All of this interaction sets him up for good behavior and sets his humans up for less well-meaning trouble to interrupt.   Leash walks will not be sufficient for meeting this guy's needs...and they do not look like the happy picture of strolling around the block that most of us are used to.  That NOSE again.   Like all committed hounds, Elvis must be on-leash or within a fenced yard at all times,  as he has a case of  "beagle selective hearing".  This means means when his nose is to the ground and he is on a scent, he turns off his hearing and won't listen to your calls despite whatever danger he may be headed towards.  

Having said all of this...to people who "get" him (his foster family and their dog-loving tribe), Elvis is hysterical, adorable and just so sweet!

Elvis has been neutered and microchipped, is heartworm negative, and is up to date on all vaccines and deworming. He is on flea and heartworm prevention, and his adoption fee is $195. 

Here at NMAR, we don't just find good homes for our dogs, we find the the specific good home for each specific dog.  Because our goal really is FOREVER homes, our write-ups are "real life" to paint true pictures, as some dogs have longer "must have lists" than others.  This is all in the spirit of our very best effort to avoid putting a dog or an adopter through returning a pup to us when the match just wasn't right for all involved.    While we work towards those matches, our dogs are safe and happy in foster homes or in our home-like shelter.  While there, they have a chance to learn some life skills and show us what they need to be happy and healthy...and to make their forever family happy and successful too.

If you've been looking for one (or two) of the world's cutest and silliest dogs, the FIRST STEP is to fill out an adoption application. Meet and greets do not occur without an approved application.  We thank you for your patience as our volunteer-run rescue reviews your information.  https://www.northmeckanimalrescue.org/adoption-information/adoption-application/

animal.description:
The short story:  Coltrane is a 40-ish pound, 3 year old, beagle/basset hound mix, who is great with other dogs, is crate-trained, and is house-broken in his routine at the shelter.  He is good with people, but he has a more reserved, introverted type of personality when he is one-on-one with a human.  Add another friendly dog who seeks out affection, and Coltrane steps up his interest level for sure!

REQUIRED: fenced yard; another playful dog in the home (or maybe adopt his brother Elvis too?); experience with the problem-solving, creativity and patience needed with hound-style hounds and their "we do things our own way" approach to life; significant distance from your neighbors as a sound buffer; a household free of young and fairly young children (due to how much awareness and organization it takes to keep a nosey and busy hound from getting into vet-requiring trouble with discarded toys and their tiny pieces,  half-finished and left-behind lunches and snacks, etc. )

A bit more detail...Coltrane loves running his silly, beagley-basset waddle in hopes of catching up to his canine friends for a good wrestle.  He also likes playing with toys, but his TRUE LOVE is "snuffling".   Coltrane is one of the two sniff-iest, snort-iest, snuffle-iest hounds we've met yet. (Elvis is the other!) This guy experiences pure joy while tracking...multiple times per day...for prolonged periods of time.  He frequently sings the Song of His Hound Dog People...loudly...while tracking.   (Insert consideration of your proximity to your neighbors here...no apartments, town homes, duplexes, or homes without very large yards).  Coltrane does great with other dogs.  While living at the rescue, he has settled into a routine well.  That said, he is used to spending a great deal of the day exploring the fenced play yards, wrestling with other dogs, playing with toys, and checking in with humans for affection on his terms while he roams the house-like areas of the rescue building.  All of this interaction sets him up for learning expectations and following routines.  Leash walks alone will not be sufficient for meeting this guy's emotional and physical needs. Like all committed hounds, Coltrane must be on-leash or within a fenced yard at all times,  as he has a case of  "beagle selective hearing".  This means means when his nose is to the ground and he is on a scent, he turns off his hearing and won't listen to your calls despite whatever danger he may be headed towards.  

Having said all of this...to people who "get" him (the volunteers who work with him at the rescue building), Coltrane is hysterical, adorable and just so sweet!

Coltrane has been neutered and microchipped, is heartworm negative, and is up to date on all vaccines and deworming. He is on flea and heartworm prevention, and his adoption fee is $195. 

Here at NMAR, we don't just find good homes for our dogs, we find the the specific good home for each specific dog.  Because our goal really is FOREVER homes, our write-ups are "real life" to paint true pictures, as some dogs have longer "must have lists" than others.  This is all in the spirit of our very best effort to avoid putting a dog or an adopter through returning a pup to us when the match just wasn't right for all involved.    While we work towards those matches, our dogs are safe and happy in foster homes or in our home-like shelter.  While there, they have a chance to learn some life skills and show us what they need to be happy and healthy...and to make their forever family happy and successful too.

If you've been looking for one (or two) of the world's cutest and silliest dogs, the FIRST STEP is to fill out an adoption application. Meet and greets do not occur without an approved application.  We thank you for your patience as our volunteer-run rescue reviews your information.  https://www.northmeckanimalrescue.org/adoption-information/adoption-application/

Beautiful Angel is an 3  yr old Shepherd mix. This beautiful girl was listed on Craigslist...litter after litter making her owner money with her pups; only worth $25 to anyone who would pay...ANYONE! Luckily, MADR was able to save Angel and her last puppy. Angel has been in a loving foster home learning how to be the best dog she can be ever since. Angel is a sweetheart who loves people and walking around town. She is a sunbather who likes to chill outside all day and loves to go on long walks and hikes. She wants to be with her people and will happily adjust to your schedule. She is smart girl and is learning basic commands and would do well with a loving family who is patient as she learns to trust new environments. She does have slight anxiety that can lead to some barking, however as she builds trust with people, that dissipates. Angel likes children and does well with dogs after a proper introduction. She seems to be afraid of cats, and stays away from them. Children 7 years old or older.  Her forever home is required to have a physically fenced yard (no invisible fences or tie outs). All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. animal.description:
ROCKY - 6 years old, house trained, 58 pounds, friendly, great on a leash, playful, active, easily startled, shrieks at times, commands SIT SHAKE/PAW DOWN, some dogs ok, cats prob ok, no small/young children.

Rocky looked very excited when I approached him. He was def ready to go outside. And I knew why once we hit the grass. He pottied right away. House trained and friendly, Rocky needs a new home. He had been with his previous family 2 years. That's a long time for a dog, a third of his life! Unfortunately however, after cuddling numerous times with his young human sibling, he snapped at her. We were told although the cuddling had been occurring and everyone was fine prior to this, on this occasion Rocky was sleeping when the little girl tried to cuddle next to him. Without getting into the why's or how's it's a simple fix. Rocky needs a new home where there are no young or small children to interrupt sleep. Supervision is a biggie when bringing a new dog into a home. Whether there are resident dogs or kids, everyone must be watched and respect everyone else. Rocky is a thick boy. He loves those treats! And he'll sit or share your hand or lie down for treats. He'll also bark if you take too much time to give him his reward. He also shrieks. You read that correctly. He shrieks at certain times. It's a bit unsettling and we're not exactly sure why he does this but it's loud. Just something for you to know. He is also easily startled. He'll back away and drop to the ground, again we're not sure why except maybe nerves. Rocky is a sweet boy looking for a new family to take him on daily walks and love him. He's easy on the eyes and also fairly easy going. Rocky is waiting at the Virginia Beach Animal Care and the Center. He's available for appointments so just call 385-4444 or go to our Facebook page and make an appointment. Bring any resident dog and/or kids in to meet him. We're open daily except for Tuesday's. 341 S Birdneck Road. Thanks for choosing adoption!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.MUST BE ADOPTED WITH HER BONDED BROTHER, GRYFFIN! NO SMALL CHILDREN - 10 OLD AND OLDERGracie is my name!

I am a little girl who was found with my litter mates in a box next to a dumpster. Who would do that to us? We were saved, and given all the love and care a little girl could ever need. And now, I am getting ready to find my forever home! I am a sweet girl, who loves to cuddle and play. I love running in the yard with the other fur kids. Mom has lots of trees and obstacles in the yard and we play tag all day long. In the house, we have a cat tunnel that we play with. It is so funny to run through and make all that crackling noise. I wait until one of my siblings is in the tunnel and then I pounce on them. They squeal - then we run and find a ball or a rope to play tug with. My favorite thing is to be on high places. I will climb on the back of one of my foster siblings so I can reach what I want to see. They don't seem to mind. My perfect family will be one where my brother Gryffin and I will be together to live out our lives. We play and sleep and need each other - even if somethings we fight, we love each other completely.
I am going to be a very small dog, so mom says NO Small Children in my future. Tiny bones break too easily.
I AM EXTREMELY BONDED WITH MY BROTHER, GRYFFIN, SO WE NEED A FOREVER HOME TOGETHER! If you are interested in meeting me, please apply! I am only doing private meetings.
=========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Meet Jaeger! He is one of the five husky mixes we saved from a life chained outside without shelter, no reprieve from the elements, and seemingly zero human interaction prior to being rescued. He is 10-11 years old and about 65 pounds. He is the absolute sweetest guy in the world. He would do best with another dog in the home who is confident and will help make him feel comfortable. He is still scared of people in general but even more so men, he has gotten a lot better but still very nervous. He does not do well around hyper children, or dogs, cats are also a big no. He also gets very upset when 'his person' leaves the home and will pace the house until they come home, so his forever home must have someone with a lot of patience that spends most of their day at home. He's never been left for more than 6 hours by himself. He likes his schedule and for his life to be predicable. If you are home with him he will request his bed be in whatever room you're in and he will sleep all day. He gives air kisses and loves butt scratches. He is a major shedder as a husky mix so requires daily brushing. Jaeger is a calm old man who just wants to spend the last years of his life feeling the way he has with is foster: safe, loved, accepted.
Applications for Jaeger @ maxxandme.org
Jaeger is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Adoption donation is only $200.
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Angel is a female brown, tan and white chihuahua. She is 5 years old and she weighs 12 pounds. Angel is spayed and vaccinated including rabies. She tested heartworm negative and is receiving monthly heartworm prevention. She is ready for adoption. 

Angel needs a home willing to let her be her. Angel learns a doggie door and her routine but she is not a dog that likes to be handled much. Angel has done well in a one-person foster home with two other dogs who mostly leave her alone. She does not warm up or want to snuggle or play with another dog. Strangely Angel seems more comfortable with a person who smokes...whether it’s the smell or the voice we aren’t sure. With a little effort to gain her trust, foster mom can pick Angel up to sit with her in her chair, and at times Angel will come ask for petting. She will not compete with other dogs for attention. Angel would do best with a doggie door. Once she learns the routine and picks her sleeping spot, Angel is no trouble. She just doesn’t seem to be that dog a little socializing can “fix” so we are seeking an easy going home that will let her find her own happiness rhythm. 

Adoption fee is $150. Must apply: Application for adoption is located at http://fs19.formsite.com/JeffTarpleyRescue/application/index.html

Our must-haves for this sweet boy include:

    A fenced yard

Oscar will always walk with a bit of a wobble, but it only adds to his charm. Please give him a chance at a lasting home, he so deserves one!  

============== Information for All Dogs/Adopters ==============

We just can't get them from one Coast to the other but some day we hope to have enough volunteers to do that as well.  For now, please look for dogs on your coast.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Female
Estimated Date of Birth: June 3, 2017
Size: 50 lbs
Location: Marietta, GA

RESCUING BABE

Babe, formerly known as Two Face, was brought into an emergency veterinary clinic in mid-May due to some difficulty urinating. She was catheterized, treated and given medicine, but her owner never came back for her. Allegedly, her owner was a rapper, arrested on murder charges. After the vet filed abandonment paperwork, Babe was surrendered to us and got her freedom ride on June 2, 2020. At the emergency clinic, she was put on antibiotics and two other medications for urinary issues. She is urinating on her own just fine and is heartworm negative.

ABOUT BABE

Babe is settling into foster care. Once she finishes up her medications, we will have her re-examined by our vet and most likely have a urinalysis done when she has been off the medications for 2 weeks. She is weary of new people, but once you gain her trust, she loves you completely and wholeheartedly. Due to her skepticism with new people, Babe will need an adult only, pit bull savvy home that will take the necessary steps and precautions to make her comfortable when meeting new people. She will meet the other dogs in her foster home once she has decompressed and fully settled into her foster home. For now, she is happy to see and sniff them through barriers like crates/gates and doesn't seem to be bothered. She will be available for adoption when she has decompressed and been fully vetted.

*Please check back for updates on this beautiful lady*

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Male
Estimated Date of Birth: May 21, 2018
Size: 75 lbs
Location: Stone Mountain, GA

RESCUING GRADY

Grady came into Paulding County Animal Control as a stray with a severe case of mange. He reminds us a lot of a dog we had years ago named Alvin. One of our awesome fosters stepped up and Grady got his freedom ride on May 21, 2020. He is being treated for his mange and underlying skin infection. He'll be fully vetted when his skin is healthy and his immune system is stronger.

ABOUT GRADY

Grady is settling into foster care and proving to be a sweet guy. Because his skin was in such poor condition, it has been a slow process to start seeing noticeable improvement, but it's getting there! He's not a huge fan of his medicated baths, but he tolerates them. Grady LOVES to eat and is very food motivated. He is also house and crate trained. He absolutely loves people and the other dogs in his foster home. He was a little too friendly with the cats and couldn't take a hint so he would probably do best in a home without cats. Grady's skin has come a long way and immune system is getting better, but he's not quite ready to be fully vetted yet. Once we get the OK from our vet, he'll be neutered and ready to go into a forever home!

*Please check back for updates!*

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
This joyful pup - Augie (AKA "Slim") - is now past the physical reminders of his rough start. He has healed wounds and started on the path to an active, loving life! Augie loves to endlessly run with his three canine housemates, wrestle with his BFF Finny, and chew on his soft toys for hours on end. He is alert to all sounds, having been aggressed on by other dogs during his first few months of life. He is desensitizing well to many fears and new situations with constant exposure. This little dude loves to ride in the car and hike on the trails (does over a mile on forested trails every morning). He is less hesitant now with new human friends and able to acclimate to new dog pals, albeit slowly and over time. This sweet, 38-pound pup is not one to go to a dog park as his ongoing fears of unknown dogs provoke him to shut down or go on the defense when introduced to new dogs. In his environment, once "acclimated" over time, he develops friendships with other well-balanced K9s, and once comfortable with them, he is the center of the party! Augie bunny hops from one location to another and one adventure to the next! He is pure love, giving smooches and cuddling as close as possible, often checking in with you! He will talk to you and wiggle that back-side to show you how glad he is to be with you!

Augie must have:

- a secure fenced-in yard.

- a doggy playmate.

- person(s) who are patient and loving . . and can spend time with him.

Augie:

- is very loving.

- has done beautifully with children.

- is 95% housetrained.

- is nondestructive when left in a room with a playmate in your absence.

- is fabulous on a leash and gentle leader; takes neighborhood walks each evening.

- is super smart; takes direction and trains easily. Loves treats and wants to please.

- barks/growls only when scared.

- is a riot!

- is extremely active.

- thinks his person(s) hung the moon and makes you feel that way!

This is sweet and clever Callie. While only with her foster a short while we can share a few observations. She is house trained. Doesnt seem to have any problems with other dogs and would likely benefit from a playful friend. She and one of them never stop playing (check it out on facebook). LOVES playing in the baby pool that has a bit of water - not sure if this would correlate to a lake? Really needs a fenced back yard (she has a history of flight, and she likes to get a good run on - is in and out all day long). Great on a leash. Does well with a 15 year old (check out facebook) but not sure yet about younger. Also not sure about cats. Does not like crates and will hurt herself trying to get out of one (and is also quite loud) - but the good news is that she appears to be quite trustworthy when left out. She just watches out windows and takes naps. She has a bark but uses it judiciously. She is very loving and will seek out attention. She is not yet quite ready for hugs around her neck, but will curl up my your side and give lots of kisses. Approved adopters please ask to meet this lovely girl!

Watch for stories, pictures and videos about me on our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/groups/40103261297/

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.I am just adorable, older children only. I need another dog for company Hi! I am Kia! I was found running down the street in a bad section of town when I was a tiny baby.
I have been having a great time with my foster brothers and sisters. I especially like the big guys mom calls Mastiffs, but I am not selective. I love the little babies too.
I have been vaccinated, spayed, microchipped and have had my rabies shot so I won't get sick. I don't potty in the house, but we have a doggie door where I can go out when I need to. I DO NOT CRATE! As hard as mom tries, I hate being crated and will hurt myself. I usually spend time in the Dining room with my friends when Mom needs me to be secure. I love sleeping with with mom at night. I am looking for a forever home where I have at least one other fur friend so I am not lonely. I love to run around the back yard chasing all the other kids so it would be great if when you adopt me, you have another small friend for me.
I don't know much about kids, but I think I would like an older boy or girl to call my own. Mom says - NO WAY CAN I BE ADOPTED by a small child. She would have to say NO WAY!
If you think I am as special as my foster mom says I am, please fill out an application. =========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Do you want to adopt me? Just go to www.dogsasfamily.org and fill out an adoption application. We do not ship our dogs and all adoptions are completed in person in the Oklahoma City, Oklahoma area. Hello, my name is Finn. I am six years old and I weigh about twenty pounds. I am a male terrier. I came to the rescue after I was found and taken to a local shelter. My family never came to claim me. That's alright with me because I needed the help of the rescue.
When I came to the rescue I tested heartworm positive. I got heartworms from a mosquito bite but I could have died without treatment. Luckily the rescue had me treated and now I am proud to say I am heartworm negative. I won't lie to you, I can be very stubborn. I am energetic, spirited, loving, devoted and amusing too. I am aggressive toward other dogs and like to 'mark' all the trees. If you want me in your life you probably better have jack or parson russell experience because I need a strong leader in my home or I will take over and misbehave. I need to be your only pet. I act fearless but will hide behind you at the vet.
I have been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. I have also had my teeth cleaned. My adoption fee is 175.00. The first step in adopting me, Finn, is to complete an application at dogsasfamily.org. You could be mine, forever.

Meet this SWEETHEART named Roxy! She came into the shelter when her owner could no longer keep her May 25, 2020. She is a sweet and beautiful girl who needs a special home that will keep her safe and give her a great life. She wants to be the queen of the home so a home without children, & no other animals is very important for Roxy. She loves being around her human friends soaking up as much body rubs and affection as one has to share. She’s always happy and wearing a smile and enjoys laying on her dog bed after playing a while. Roxy is 9 years old, current on shots, already spayed and seems house broken. Just a great girl! Might you have the most am amazing FOREVER home for this sweetie?! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description: In september 2019 my friend of 10 years Erin, who lived in louisiana, passed away suddenly from a heart condition. His father works 16 hour days in Texas making it impossible for him to care for the 2 senior family pets left behind. The likelihood of the dogs to end up in a shelter concerned me knowing that senior dogs rarely get adopted. After the funeral, I brought Hermes and gizmo on the long journey back to Tennessee with me and my family. All hermes and gizmo ever knew was the comfort and safety of their home with Erin. They are not used to a busy lifestyle as they were not socialized with other animals or children. Gizmo is a 13 year old male, neutered, chipped, and utd on his shots. He is very food motivated but will need to be kept on a diet so he doesnt over eat. He is allergic to chicken and freshly cut grass. He will get really red and itchy. He has a prescription for apoquel for these allergies. Gizmo is also afraid of thunderstorms and has a thunder shirt to help ease his anxiety. Gizmo like company especially when doing his business. If he doesnt have a bathroom buddy, he may wait and go in the house. Gizmo is not a fan of cats or small children. Hermes is a 10 year old male, neutered, chipped, and utd on shots. He is very introverted which I believe is due to him having sporadic seizures. He may take a while to warm up to someone new, but he is a very sweet boy once you earn his trust. Hermes is food agressive toward other animals. Gizmo knows to give him space. Hermes is also allergic to chicken and has storm anxiety. He has a thundershirt as well. He does well with not going potty in the house. They would do well in a home together with no other pets and little foot traffic. I

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Say hello to Optimus!

He is currently at the Islip Animal Shelter in Bay Shore, NY where our favorite senior buddy Wally came from!

Optimus came to the shelter in December 2019 with 9 other dogs that were all used for breeding. When the owner didn't need them anymore he stopped feeding and caring for them! Optimus was found running loose and the shelter took him in. He had a lot of wounds and was in very rough shape. But now he is all healed up and ready to find his furever home!

Optimus must be your only pet, but with that handsome face who needs any other animals?! He deserves all the love and then some! He absolutely adores people and would be fine with kids who are 10+. Optimus would love a fenced-in yard where he can roam and enjoy life. He has a little sway in his step so he doesn't run too much. This is likely due to being crated 24/7 for most of his life. Don't let that fool you! He still likes to play and go on adventures!

In order to get him to Buffalo, we need a foster home or adopter for him! If you think this sweet man would be a great addition to your family, please fill out an application!Adoption donation includes Spay/Neuter, UTD on Vaccinations, deworming, and flea treatment.

animal.description:
Meet Samson
Poor Samson. This boy must have lived a lonely and frightening life by the time he arrived. Samson had been running around for weeks and nearly got hit by traffic before he was taken to Animal Control. We rescued Samson just as fast as we could and brought him to the safety of our shelter. We gave Samson some time to decompress. He’s now ready for his forever family. 
Samson was so frightened when he first arrived. Every day he learns to trust a bit more. We think he must have been horribly abused and neglected. Samson is a Staffordshire terrier mix. He’s about three years old. He weighs 65 lbs. He’s extremely handsome with a beautiful coat and markings. 
Samson is an active boy. He loves having a fenced yard to freely run and romp. He loves taking walks. He sits patiently in his kennel to be leashed up, knowing he’s going out to sniff and smell and stretch his legs. He can be a strong walker though and would do best with an active and agile person to keep up with him. He’s extremely smart and has picked up many commands – sit, wait, stay, shake, kiss, and hug – the last two are our favorites!
Samson sits and waits for treats, and he’ll take them gently from your hand. He loves attention, when he knows you. And he’s so appreciative of the kind and gentle hands that pet him. He is often seen laying on his blanket quietly chewing on his Nyla bone. A kennel, a blanket and a bone must seem like heaven for this boy. We think Samson might be house-trained. He keeps his kennel clean and seems to do his business outside. 
Samson is selective about other dogs. He doesn’t seem to care for ‘alpha’ male dogs, but enjoys the company of females and younger puppies. Samson has encountered cats and he will lunge for them, but not aggressively. It seems he’s more curious, but we’ll test for potential adopters. Samson would do best in a quiet, yet active home, given he’s still unsure of the world around him. Samson wants to engage with his person and be a part of their activities. He wants to know he belongs to someone. He’s very loyal to those who have shown him kindness and spend time with him. Patience and a steady-hand will help Samson continue to blossom. 
He’s a gem in the making and just needs some continued TLC to ease his fears and let him know how important he is. If you’re looking to make a wonderful dog’s dream of a loving home come true, Samson may be your boy.
Samson will be neutered, micro-chipped and fully vetted before going home. 
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
Star comes to NGPR after her adoring owner sadly passed away. She has lived a long life full of love and is now looking for the Pyrfect retirement home that will show her just as much love as her owner did. Star is a sweet, low-energy girl who wants to be with her humans. She is house trained and absolutely loves going for walks. Star gets a little anxious when left alone but rewards you with lots of love and affection when you stay home with her. She is extremely loyal and will follow you wherever you go. Star thinks she is a lap dog and will climb right up for a cuddle :) She needs lots of reassurance that she is safe during thunderstorms and like a typical Pyr, she will protect your home from any incoming threats or intruders. Star is looking for a quiet home to live out her golden years--which means being the only dog as she becomes a 'Queen' when encountering other dogs and wants them banished from her kingdom so she can be the center of your attention and relax in peace. Star has lived with cats and does great with children who understand how to respectfully interact with an older dog. Star’s foster family says she is the sweetest, most lovable dog they have ever known. If you can give this girl the 'Star'  retirement she is looking for, apply for this sweet girl today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

Meet Norman, a 8.5 year old "pocket" Mastiff Mix weighing in at a petite 84 pounds! Norman was surrendered to a shelter last year, where a volunteer decided to change his life forever and bring him home to be safe. The shelter has limited capacity to place giant breeds, so she reached out to us and Norman is officially a BDHP man! This sweet old guy is very scared of strangers and needs a calm, quiet retirement home that can give him lots of belly rubs. He knows to sit, roll over, and shake, and loves to meander around his backyard and take naps. Norman is working on his manners with other dogs but is content to sniff them through fences and hang out by himself. Due to his fear, he will require a home with older children (if any) and a quieter environment. If you can provide a retirement home for this special guy to live out his golden years, he will say "thanks" with lots of snuggles and kisses!

Golden Rewards Program All of our adoptable grey muzzled gentle giants who are at least 7 years young are available for adoption for a reduced $250 donation!

Already a Golden Rewards Club member? If you've adopted a senior gentle giant from Big Dogs Huge Paws in the past, we have great news for you! Adopt a second senior for a Golden Rewards Club adoption donation of $200, and if it's your third senior dog adoption we are offering a special Golden Rewards Club reduced donation of only $150! Why wait?

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Emmett is a 7 year old Purebred American Bulldog who came to us after his owner fell ill and was no longer able to care for him. Emmett lived alone with a senior citizen most of his life, so he can be wary at first when he meets new people. Once you are in his “circle,” he is an extremely loving and affectionate dog that loves to be pet. Emmett is a strong dog that is still very playful and enjoys the company of other animals. Emmett would do best in a quiet adult household that has experience with large breed dogs.

animal.description:
Meet Danielle... This cute little girl was picked up as a stray and just a few days later became ill with the deadly parvovirus. Thankfully, she’s one tough cookie and beat the odds and is now happy and healthy. She appears to be a terrier mix of some sort with her cute little nub tail. She photographes bigger than she is. She only weighs around 15 lbs and will not get any bigger. She’s playful and full of personality. She definitely would benefit from having another pup, kids and a yard to play in. She’s the perfect family pet. She’s utd, dewormed and spayed. This girl is ready for her forever home. Get your apps in and don’t miss out on this cuteness. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

Being older and having to be the only pet already makes her chances slim to find her forever family easily but having cancer and only a short time to live was the ultimate heartache. animal.description:
MOCHI (HW NEG)

SPAYED FEMALE - AKITA MIX - 3 YRS

This poor girl arrived at her shelter as just a puppy when she was THROWN OVER AN 8 FOOT GATE!! Luckily she was adopted, but unfortunately, Mochi started having some medical issues that may have been caused when she was tossed like garbage over the fence. She has some neurological issues that cause her to bunny hop with her front feet and her head bobs when she runs. Despite these little tics, she is still a very active girl that loves to play! She has also almost completely lost her eyesight (she has 5% vision). Due to her blindness, Mochi needs routine and a calm environment. Her blindness will cause her to be startled with fast movements or loud noises (understandably so!). Her first adopter did not know how to care for a blind girl, so she was not set up for success. It was a very active household with kids, and that was not the place for Mochi. When dealt with properly, however, she does great with people and dogs! She allows herself to be handled and has done well with her vet. Mochi just needs someone who will be patient and understanding that she has special needs! Will that be you?
Mochi requires a home with a yard. She doesnt like to go on walks. Her favorite thing is to dig for sticks and roots in her yard. No children please. No cats. 
 

 

 

 

 

 

ON A WALK: https://youtu.be/Mvoc9yIg1NM

VIDEO OF HER STORY: https://youtu.be/dy9CzULChd4

Hey there friends, they call me the Dogtor! I love to run, jump, and play, (especially with toys that squeak!) but at the end of the day I just really would love a family who can spend quality time with me (which sometimes means naps, because who doesn't like naps?!).

animal.description:
Tye is a 1 1/2 year old Cane Corso that has been through so much in his young life. He was found as a stray puppy in January, 2020. He had cherry eyes, which we repaired, and Tye was quickly adopted. Unfortunately, Tye was returned for not getting along with the other dog in the home, and returned yet again due to his owner's not being able to care for a large dog. The second time Tye came back, he arrived with an injured hind leg. We sent Tye for surgery for a luxating patella and then he spent several weeks doing physical therapy. Tye is finally ready for the best home ever! Tye is such a sweet, goofy boy. All he wants is to offer you his big paw and get lots of attention. Tye has not had much training in his life and he can be a little mouthy while playing, so he'll need a home with older kids. He also needs a pet-free home. He's just a giant puppy that loves to run and play. He's a big leaner, leaning against you to get as much attention as you'll give him. He would love to be offered a great home where he can stay forever and ever! File#29445 6/26/20 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an appointment to meet Tye.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

Cali will need management surrounding her crate, food, and toys.  We have started her on a management program that is working well and will need to be followed in her new home.  She needs to have leadership defined in a non confrontational way and does best with male humans.  Cali is good off leash and loves to hike and run in the woods.  She loves car rides and is eager to go off on an adventure. Cali is ok with most dogs, although would prefer to live as a solo dog or with a goofy male that allows her to be the boss.  She is ok with dog savvy cats who don't run.  Cali is house trained and has nice manners inside.  Please have breed experience prior to applying.

We took him in and were lucky enough to find a great foster who has shown him more love and care in a few weeks than he has probably had in his life. He's doing great in his foster home and enjoys his bunkmates, but he's anxious to hit the road and find a forever person or family he could love and enjoy life with. COURTESY POST - READ ALL NOTES BELOW BEFORE INQUIRING: 
Hi there!  My name is Cheeks and I'm one of the founding members of the Bad Boys Club.  I'm 3 years old and I've got a bully attitude, gallons of drool and rollz for days.  I've been trained by No Bull Rehab and have learned the skills to help me be successful in my forever home. I don't see very well, which caused me some challenges at first but now that I'm more comfortable, I'm even conquering ramps and steps.  I need a home with NO kids and NO other animals that can devote the time to coming to Covina to work with my trainers.  My ideal home will sign up for 4-5 sessions with my trainer, learn about me and my training, learn the tools they use to help me communicate properly and will listen and follow ALL instructions given. My adoptive home should be aware that my trainers mean business! Everything I learned will be transferred and implemented into my new home for total success! Think you've got what it takes?  Contact Summer at summer.parker@yahoo.com for more info!  #cheeks4president

animal.description:
SINGLE MALE LOOKING FOR SINGLE FEMALE. I am looking for cuddles, snuggles, and love. I prefer quiet nights at home instead of a party. I love to cuddle on the couch and watch a good movie. I love to go on walks and hikes. I can also spend all day in my bed being lazy! I am a young male just searching for love! I am neat, tidy, very potty trained, and enjoy food and treats. You see, I'm a dog and my name is Scooby. I am 5 years old, a Cairn terrier mix, and weigh about 14 pounds full grown. I am professionally trained to sit, lay down, stay, heel, and come when on leash. I come with two additional training sessions. I take a while to bond with people and greatly prefer females over males. I am leery of strangers but once I know you my eyes will light up and I'll dance for you. I have been waiting a long time for a home since I do not make a great first impression. I would do great as on only dog as I entertain myself with toys and don't like to share them. I'm not fond of dogs, cats or kids. I'm great in a car and love walks and hikes. I am house broken, and kennel trained. I sleep in my foster mom's bedroom in a crate quiet as a mouse. I love being able to see my person sleeping. I must have a kid and cat free home, and I must have a yard no apartments. --- He is neutered, up to date on vaccines, vet checked and microchipped. His adoption fee is $100 which includes a free vet visit. To do a meet and greet, contact the foster Dr. Kim at

Raja von Ranis is a striking-looking, 18-month-old Kelpie mix. From a namesake meaning ‘king,’ this stunning boy is in search of an experienced adult home. He can be unsure of strangers and touch, and  his loyalty is strong — leading him to be somewhat protective of  his human(s).  With some time, training and exposure to new people and situations, Raja will learn that he can relax and enjoy his life as a puppy! He’s a little shy and cautious with new people at first, so proceeding slowly to gain his trust and favor will go a long way. Gentle introductions and getting him used to new sights and smells will help Raja live his best life. He does seem comfortable around other pups, and is happy to be in doggy playgroup. Raja is ready to meet you and bond with you for a lifetime to come! 

VIDEO !!


Westside dog Biographies, availability and new photos are updated regularly on our website! So, check in and log on often! 

Westside thanks you for looking at our amazing dogs and for choosing to save an animal's life through rescue. 

Don't forget to visit your local animal shelter...the source of many of our dogs.
 

www.sheprescue.org

https://www.facebook.com/WGSRescue

animal.description:
Yaso is about 3 years old, and currently in the low 50lbs range.

He's a happy boy that appears to get along with other dogs but definitely benefits from the slow, patient introductions that we recommend with any dog (regardless of breed or history).

Due to his desire to be around his people a lot, he would do best in a home where someone is mostly home due to his separation anxiety. He will dig out of yard if left alone, so does need company! If left alone, he probably does best if crated. 
We would recommend he go to a home with confident adults only.

Yaso rides well in car.  He also walks well on leash. 

As his foster Mom says, he's a "real lover boy".

We have not tested him with cats, other small critters, or small children yet, but would expect him to have a normally high prey drive for smaller, wild animals (squirrels, rabbits etc).

Contact us for more information, and visit our website to complete an adoption application form:

www.twodogfarms.com/adopt

Adoption fees are $350.00.

info@twodogfarms.com

MEET SNOOK!!

CHECK OUT MY VIDEOS IN TRAINING!! Video 1: https://youtu.be/6OQWJcjqUfc

Video 2: https://youtu.be/vjfrAuuAa2E

And just look at my smile!! I am a 3 year old, neutered, happy go lucky boy!!

I have had PROFESSIONAL training, and come with additional FREE training to my adoptive family!

I absolutely love the water!! It would be wonderful to be adopted into a home with a pool, or at least a kiddie pool in the backyard!

I am friendly with other dogs, but am not real good with small ones, so I probably will not do well with cats.
I also would do best in a home without smaller kids-- 10+ would be best.

I have my calm moments and then I have moments where I can be playfull and want to run around and have fun. I am already crate trained and housebroken and I have learned all my basic obedience commands including how to Heel on leash!

I have one quirk, I am absolutely terrified of large brimmed hats and sunglasses. So whoever my adopter is needs to be aware that these scare me.

Snooks adopter will be required to continue with (8)

follow up training sessions with Partners in Cave Creek (Free of charge) during his Foster With Intent to Adopt trial period. This way, his adopter will learn the same tools that Snook has been taught with, to continue with his success of being the perfectly mannered dog!

animal.description:
Meet out sweet Lilly. This girl came from a situation where she was unsocialized and not given much attention. When she was surrendered to us, her high energy and lack of manners made her a great candidate for our prison training program. She has done well there, learning her basics and leash walking. .

Lilly loves to play. She has a big red ball, that she will chase for hours. She would be an excellent addition to any soccer team! She is sweet and loving to humans, but also very independent. She's a great size, and just beautiful. 

This girl needs a home without small animals or cats, She would probably prefer to be the only dog in the household. Children over ten who could handle her exuberance would find a wonderful companion to grown up with.

Lilly can climb and jump just about anything, so she must have yard with a secure fence at least 6 feet tall.

Our dogs are fed a nutrient rich dog food named NutriSource.  Our experience is a high quality dog food keeps vet bills down and well-being high.

If you have any questions please email: claudiaatwag@gmail.com

Visit our website to fill out an Adoption Application  http://www.wagsequimwa.com

Adoption donation fee $400  (Please understand this adoption donation goes towards helping all the dogs we rescue)

animal.description: I am a cat in a dog's body, so please treat me like you would a cat. Except I'm better than a cat, because I'm a dog'. Albus is still figuring out how this beloved family dog thing works. It takes him a bit of time to warm up to new people, but the more you spend time with him, the more he'll start nudging your hand and leaning into you for pets. When he's really comfortable, he'll plow his head right into your hands and beg for massages. He's very in tune with his person's feelings, and will put his head on your knee, looking lovingly into your eyes, falling head over heels in love. When he smiles, Albus' face shines as bright as the sun. Once you've earned his trust, this sweet guy will do anything for you. He's very treat-motivated (and loves apples!), so that can help speed things along. In his foster home, Albus has proven to be an excellent houseguest. He's house-trained, does well left home alone, and loves hanging out in his crate. It's his safe space and he sleeps all through the night in there. He also thrives on routines, especially for feeding. Albus has a nice low to medium energy level, walks easily on leash and gives amazing eye contact. While at the shelter, he enjoyed going to playgroup with his canine friends and could go home with a well-matched doggie sibling. Albus is a smart pup and has made great strides in APA!'s Total Obedience Program, which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Albus has a personalized training plan to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! He's learning skills like sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, answering to 'sit' and 'down' until told 'free,' coming when called and 'place,' which means he will go to a specific place in your home on command. And as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with him after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 This sweet old soul would love a quiet home where he can slip into a nice routine. Come meet Albus, he'll be the most loving and loyal companion you could hope for! Follow Albus on Instagram @albus_thepupper.

animal.description:
Sugar belonged to the surrendering owner's husband.  When he passed away and she was unable to care for her or brother, Jackson.  They were kenneled outside so appreciate being in a safe, warm house.  

With a guesstimated birthday in June 2018, Sugar is ready to sweeten your life.  She's house-trained when kept on a regular schedule and leash-savvy.  She's a little nervous in cars, but enjoys the adventure once she arrives.  

Sugar is good with people and polite male dogs.  She doesn't like female dogs, but is well-behaved when on leash.  She has been around cats and will play chase-the-cat, but can be called off.

She has been invited to visit the neighborhood daycare and loves the little ones.  She would prefer to be an only dog in her home as she loves her people and would rather not share attention.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience.

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description: Poor Theo… this guy needs a warm and loving home…Our new boy Theo has had a rough way to go and he is still fighting for a good life… Theo came to GRRAND from a hoarding situation with 80 other dogs and he was found in a crate, in absolutely DEPLORABLE conditions… just a terrible situation for those dogs! He is extremely scared as we can only imagine, and he is a pretty sick guy too, as he was just diagnosed with cardiomyopathy which is a heart disease. He is in the hospital as tests are being run and we are doing what we can to help Theo pull through this! He has never known a loving pet, a warm home or what TLC is all about… He is about to learn! He is a senior boy in desperate need of a wonderful loving family to hang out with for the rest of his days and get smothered in all of the affection he can handle! We will update as we learn more and if you would like to donate to help GRRAND with Theo’s vet bills, please visit the DONATE tab on the GRRAND main website page. Visit http://grrand.org/online-adoption-application/ to access our online application. You do not need to fill out an application for each dog you are interested in learning more about. Once your application is reviewed a GRRAND volunteer will contact you to begin the process. Our Adoption Placement Coordinator will work with you to find a dog with the characteristics to best fit your family. Please visit our website at www.grrand.org for information about our adoption procedures and the areas we service.

Rappini is approx 1 year old 56 lbs.  He is a playful puppy.  He looks like a bassador, part lab  and part basset.  We know his mom was a black lab mix.  He is what we call a low rider,, short legs and longish body.  He's a very smart dog and can be a little shy with new people, but loves to run and play with his rescue buddies.  He seems to be pretty well house trained  and does pretty well on a leash.  He needs a home with a yard as he loves to run and play, he loves toys and will sit patiently for his treats.  He does not have a mean bone in his body.  He absolutely needs a doggy buddy to play with and a fenced yard

OUR RESCUE POLICY - It is our rescue policy for all our dogs that we require a home with no children under the age of 8, and experienced dog owners only.  

 

The total adoption fee of  between $550  and includes the required interstate health certificate and transport , spay/neuter, shots including rabies, bordatella, parvo, distemper and canine influenza, and microchip.  The total amount is payable to Shaggy Dog Rescue which is  a 501c3.   We also provide a coupon for a free wellness visit to the South Wilton Vet group if convenient for you.

animal.description:
bailey is a 3-year-old, rough and tumble, loving and lovable, low rider pit mix.  bailey was pulled from ACCTPhilly in February, 2020, with pneumonia and a torn ACL.  it took several weeks to beat the pneumonia, but bailey has recovered 100%.  she was the best patient!  for her ACL, bailey was getting laser therapy and water therapy, and is now fully healed. 

bailey LOVES to ride in the car!  she loves snap peas, baby carrots, apple slices, and bananas.  she loves peanut butter and frozen pup cups.  she goes on walks with a dog friend close in size to her. she walks well on a halter though can pull very hard.  once she is familiar with where she is, she walks with a loose leash.  she loves to look out the window but rarely barks.  her tail wags faster than any dog's tail anywhere.  she loves her squeaky toys and braided toys.  she is very smart, and while she enjoys enrichment toys, she figures them out very quickly.  she appreciates slow introductions with treats.  she is not a fan of fireworks (who is?).  she sleeps well in bed, sometimes under the covers.  she prefers a warm fire during the colder months and to wear a coat when walked.  in the summer, she likes to lay on a blanket in the grass (the grass is itchy to her skin).  she buries herself under all the couch pillows with just a nose or a tail poking out.  she watches dogs on tv.  she tiptoes in streams but is not a fan of the rain.  she is happy sleeping in a crate or taking a time out as long as she has a good chew toy.  she gladly goes in her crate after you toss some treats in.  we say "Go to beds".  if she hears activity going on and she is not included because she is in the crate, she will whine and whimper.    bailey is a really, really, really good sleeper.  bailey is a really, really, really good snorer.  bailey can keep herself occupied but nothing makes her happier than when she can play with you.  she wants to know what you are cooking, what you are eating, and when you are ready to play.  she is happy to be with you, wherever you are.

i would not recommend she live with kids or cats.  she plays rough and is jumpy.

baily eats fresh pet and dry food.  she gets fed in the morning and at night.  she gets walked in the morning before b-fast, at lunch, and at night.  she poops twice per day
