FAST FACTS:
*Potty and Crate Trained
*Dog Friendly 
*No Young Kids Under 10
*No Apartments/Condos
*Fenced Yard Preferred
*No Cats
*Training Required

BIO:
Looking for a friendly, fun-loving Fella? Here I am! I'm a handsome, super sweet pittie-mix prince - estimated to be about 2 years old and 60 pounds - who is available for adoption through Fetching Tails Foundation. My foster mom says I am a good mix of active goofball and cuddly. When I'm in a playful mood, I enjoy chasing my tail, playing with all the toys and bones I can get my paws on, and running some zoomies. Once I am all tired out from our fun and adventures, I am a pro snuggler and will make myself at home next to you on the couch. Because of my mouthy play style I would do best in a home with children who are older (10+) while I work on my manners and learn more appropriate ways to play. I get along with other dogs with the help of slow introductions and time to get to know each other, but no kitty cats for me, please.  

As a young guy, I need a family who will commit to continuing training with me so I can be the best Fella around! I'm potty trained and love my crate; I do fine in my personal man cave while my foster parents are at work during the day and sometimes I even take my toys and go rest in my crate without prompting! I am a talker so I would prefer a single-family house without shared walls instead of an apartment or townhouse, and a fenced yard that I could enjoy would be a big bonus! I'm working on basic commands including sit, wait, stay, and down, and I would love to learn even more with you by my side. I aim to please my people and just need some guidance and structure to thrive. Do you think I could be the goofy and loving Fella for you? Please get in touch with my friends at Fetching Tails soon! I can't wait to meet you!

Kisses and cuddles,
Fella

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess. If any questions please email us!

animal.description: Ho I am so, so happy to be here.... You see I was found in town by a very caring, wonderful lady and she brought me to the shelter. The lady was crying because I looked so bad. I have had lots and lots of puppy in my day and so I was in pretty bad shape. I was so, so skinny too. Now I look great and ready for my new family. I look totally different from when I came here and the lady that brought me here gets updates on me and she is so happy for me. She too wants me to find a loving, caring home. I do not ever had to have any more kids to take care of. When I get my new family someone will be taking care of little me. I am about three years old. I sometimes get to come into the office and I have the best time playing with the other dogs.... We play with the toys and have the best time... I love it. People do not recognizes me either.Just the other day  when I was in the office I heard someone say " Is that Judith!  Wow, she looks so good". I may have been a stray but now I am wonderful and looking for my furever home.  My adoption fee is $100 and this includes my shots, worming and yea,,,,, spaying..... no more kids ! Also micro chipping.  If you would like to adopt me do not come to the shelter.  You must first call, email, or  Facebook the shelter to fill out an application for me and then an appointment to come get me and finish the adoption  process. I am looking forward to that day.... I am Judith

animal.description:
Bruno Mars was an owner release to the rescue. He is a big happy dog! He loves people and cuddling. He is very calm but active. He is about 2 years old and is a beautiful black & white color. He loves to chew bones and is mellow but VERY strong. Bruno Mars is a big fella at around 70 lbs. He needs an active home, with a mom or dad who is able to wrangle a big guy.

He is currently taking training classes to learn how to not pull on a leash and not get overexcited when seeing other dogs. While he's been mostly all right around other dogs, he has become aggressive a couple of times. We are looking for a home where he could be the only dog and have all the attention. We are working on teaching him to greet other dogs appropriately with training right now, but this is mostly so that he will behave like a gentleman in public. Bruno is housebroken and crate trained.

Someone who has a flexible schedule and the time to train, exercise, and properly care for him is a must. He needs focus and attention. He really is a big teddy bear though! He would LOVE to snuggle on the couch or sleep in a bed, he is a really chill dog. He needs a good, safe, secure yard to play in. He would make a great hiking buddy. But due to his size, we would recommend no toddlers or young children in his new home. 

Bruno is currently in foster in the Seattle area. His adoption fee includes his neuter, up-to-date basic vaccines, rabies vaccine, and microchip.

Please complete an application at the following link:

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

Questions? Contact us at connellpetrescue@gmail.com 

Thank you!

AT PEPPERMINT PIG ANIMAL RESCUE, WE UPDATE ALL OF OUR PETS ON A REGULAR BASIS. 

IF YOU SEE ME HERE, I AM AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. PLEASE READ MY BIO BELOW TO LEARN MORE ABOUT ME AND HOW TO APPLY TO ADOPT :)

Meet ¡Queso! 48 pounds, 2 years old, Neutered Male Labrador/Border Collie mix.

Available for Adoption!

ADOPTION FEE SPONSORED

This spunky and spirited little guy is searching for his forever home! ¡Queso! is a little softy once her warms up to you and gives lots of affection and kisses. He bonds deeply and quickly to his person and would do best in a single person home without children, other dogs or small animals. ¡Queso! would make an excellent running partner or agility dog with some training! ¡Queso! is super smart and would benefit from obedience training and an active lifestyle. He absolutely LOVES running and playing in a securely fenced yard but would also do well as a walking, jogging or running partner where all activities take place on a leash. ¡Queso! is housebroken, has good in-home manners, and does well when crated. 

$0 ADOPTION FEE, ADOPTION FEE HAS BEEN SPONSORED! 

A $10.00 non-refundable application fee is required to submit your adoption application and will be deducted from your adoption fee if you adopt.

All Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue dogs are spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations, heartworm tested, current on heartworm and flea prevention, and microchipped.

A Fenced Yard is preferred for ¡Queso! but not required to adopt. 

Please see our Fenced Yard Requirements tab on our website for more information, here:
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/fenced-yard-requirements/

Our adoption area, unless otherwise specified in their bio, is within a two hour radius of Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue for adult dogs, and within a one hour radius for puppies. 

Please see our Adoption Radius tab on our website for more info, here:
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/adoption-radius/

TO CHECK AVAILABILITY of any of our adoptable animals, please go to our available pets tab, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/available-pets-for-adoption/

All pets listed here are CURRENTLY AVAILABLE.

ADOPTION APPLICATION INSTRUCTIONS FOR PEPPERMINT PIG ANIMAL RESCUE:

Before completing the application, please read our ADOPTION PROCESS tab on our website, here: 
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/how-our-adoptions-work/

To complete our easy online adoption application, please visit our website at PeppermintPigAnimalRescue.org.

All adoption information and applications can be found under the ADOPTION CENTER tab.

Adoption events are held every Saturday in our thrift store from 1:00pm to 4:00pm. Please complete your adoption application in advance so our volunteers have time to screen and contact potential adopters.

IMPORTANT: All applications are reviewed in the order they are received and qualifications are based on best fit for each individual pet. A volunteer will contact you if you are selected for a meet with adoptable pet. Final approval is always made in person.

Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue is a no-kill rescue. Please consider sponsoring a pet or donating to our cause. Click the DONATE tab on our website to learn more about how you can help. THANK YOU !

For questions or inquiries on our adoptable pets, please feel free to contact our volunteer rescue team directly by submitting a Contact Form from our website, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/contact-us/

If you are interested in adopting Rio please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte is responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

animal.description:
Cookies n' Cream is 1 to 3 years old. He has a Dalmatian white and black ticking coat and a Staffie body. He is a cutie! Very loving with people - even strangers. He does not like small spaces. So he would love a forever home with a nice sized yard.
He came to us because his people did not have permission to have him where they live.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Zion is a beautiful tan and dark brown brindle color with white on his chest and belly. One ear sticks straight up and the other flops down.
 He may not be named for Zion Williamson, but he would definitely shatter the Duke canine vertical jump record! In addition to his impressive jumping ability (dont worry, he has had no interest in jumping fences), Zions award-winning smile and incredible athleticism continue the analogy. Zion could certainly beat Carolina down the courtor at least accompany you on a nice jog, followed up by some play time. As an added bonus, Zion sometimes uses walks as an opportunity to get in some resistance training, although he has been using a no-pull harness to tamp down on his fitness urges. He also loves to stop and sniff. Everyone has to take it easy sometimes, after all! Zions amiable nature makes him a good companion for dogs who can match his energy level, although he definitely has a dominant personality. On leash, Zion has done extremely well with every dog he has met. He might not have a degree from Duke, but Zion is an A+ student. He can already sit, lay down, stay, leave it and give a nice high five. Because he is so smart, Zion will need a good coach to keep his progress going. After a hard day of press interviews, this social butterfly loves nothing better than to curl up on the couch and cuddle. He falls into a deep sleep with his head in your lap and wags his adorable, crooked tail to sweet dreams of playing with his favorite people. If you're relaxed, Zion will just hang out. If you want to go out and adventure, Zion is all in! Smart, lovable, and easy on the eyes...what cant he do?
Like the former Duke favorite and future NBA great, Zion values one thing above all else: family. Zion doesnt like to be left alone, and can become upset if his team isnt around to have his back. Zion would do best in a house where someone in the family works from home or in a family with opposite work schedules. Zion has been responding well to anxiety medication and could also do well in a household where his people can arrange for some afternoon attention or come home for lunch. Because of his separation anxiety, Zion is still working on becoming comfortable spending time in a crate and cannot yet be left alone in a crate. His loud bark would definitely reach the press box in Cameron Indoor Stadium, and he often uses it from his perch at the front window to let you know that your Amazon package has arrived (thanks, Z!). For this reason, he would do best in a stand-alone home with a fenced yard. Zion also moonlights as a counter-surfercowabunga! Because of his fascination with all things small and furry (helloooo, squirrels!), we think that Zion would likely not be the best companion for feline friends, although he has not been cat tested. Hes still young and has a lot to learn, but with some patience and training, Zion will be a Hall-of-Famer for sure.
 Zion was an unclaimed stray at a rural shelter.
 Read more about Zion on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-20-119/.

animal.description:
Here's Rex!

Before we say anything else, Rex will need a special home. He cannot and will not go to just any home. Please read his bio before applying. He's a 4 year old hound mix.

Rex has been a difficult case. He was referred to us by Gentle Jake's Coonhound Rescue, and surrendered after his owner passed away unexpectedly. Rex was used to guarding his salvage yard property, so he needs patience with new people. Once he is fully settled in with his new people, he is quite friendly and sweet, and loves belly rubs and lying in the sunshine.
He is low energy and just wants to keep his people company.

Rex would do best in a country property where he has space to be a dog and do his thing. His new owner should be a confident male or couple, with no children, and someone who will commit to continuing Rex's training.

Rex will come with 3 mandatory, complimentary, on site training sessions, courtesy of North Grey K9.

If you think you can handle this guy, or you know someone who sounds like a good match due this cool dude, you can fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/91594053676264 and SHARE, SHARE, SHARE to help find this boy his perfect home!

Rex has gotten a second chance and we are thrilled to be able to help him. He is also being treated for an ear infection, and will only be adopted after he is clear of it.

Located near Owen Sound

Rex's adoption fee is discounted to $350, which includes:
- up to date vaccines
- 1 month flea prevention
- 3 complimentary training sessions with North Grey K9
- 6 weeks free pet insurance
- gift bag of goodies from us
- bag of food

If you would like to donate toward Rex's care, please do so by etransfer or PayPal to email rayray1632@gmail.com.

Thank you to North Grey K9 and Gentle Jake's for the teamwork in saving this boy!
He is a great dog who deserves the best!

animal.description:
Spook is a 1 year old hound mix who came to us from Animal Control. He is full of energy, loves meeting new people and has done well when playing with other dogs.

Canine Companions at the animal center are all good citizens because they have been altered prior to availability for adoption.  I have received at least my first vaccination for parvo, distemper, adenovirus, coronavirus and bordatella (kennel cough) and possibly more dependant on my age and how long I have been at the center.  If the dog is 12 weeks old it may have received a rabies vaccination.  All canines are dewormed on intake and at regular intervals.  All parasites are also treated such as fleas and ticks as well.  All dogs 6 months of age and older are tested for heartworm disease and all dogs regardless of age are place on heartworm preventative.  All dogs are microchipped so that if they get lost they can find their way back home to you quickly.  All pets adopted from the center come with a one month free pet insurance which will help to ensure their health and well-being. 
The animal center does its best to help assure that the adopting person and or family finds a pet suitable and compatable for your lifestyle.  
Purebred canine adoption fee is $125.  Puppies up to 4 months $125.  Dogs over 4 months $100.  Some of our canine friends have been sponsored by generous patrons- this allows the adoption fee to be reduced from original fee minus sponsorship amount to good homes.

animal.description:
Mabel is the best of both worlds, a protective, loyal pup and the biggest lap dog you'll ever meet!! She doesn't mind spending the night in her crate but she would much rather be curled up beside your bed so she can keep a close and loving eye on you. She is completely house trained and will ask to go out if needed. She is remarkably relaxed and spends her day taking endless naps and basking in the sun but also enjoys a fun game of fetch. We feel Mabel would do best in a home with no other animals or small children. Apply to adopt sweet Mabel today!

I know I may look a little intimidating but my foster mom says I'm the gentlest girl with lots of love and kisses to give! I would be so grateful to find my forever home.I am about 3/4 years old, potty trained, mellow, and loyal. I have been at Wonder Paws for a over a year since they saved me from a high kill shelter hours before they aborted my babies. I have had 1 application but they decided to take home another dog that was younger and more playful. Don't let my laidback personality fool you. I am always up for a good game of tug of war. I am loved & spoiled at my foster mom's home but I can't stop dreaming of a family to call my own. I promise I'll be your best friend forever if you give me a chance. All I ask is for yummy meals, a cozy spot to nap on, and to be the only pup in a quiet home.

To adopt:

https://wonderpaws.wufoo.com/forms/dog-adoption-application/

Mabel will come with up to date vaccines, spayed, negative HW & fecal test, free vet visit, and lifetime microchip registration.

animal.description:
Howdy there! My name is Maxx and I'm probably the dog for you.

 I'm a 5 year old, confident, very active, fun all day long GSD mix. I was pulled from the shelter. Previously, I lived with a family with kids most of my life, but unfortuantely I was allowed to run around too much and that got me into trouble. It seems I really like chasing animals, especially chickens. Yum! 

Did you check out my video of me doing some sweet moves on the agility course? That is only half of what I can do! I have a high ball drive and good focus. That means I have great potential as a sport dog or working dog. And on top of that, I love the water! The trainer at EDCGSR said I have great potential, good energy, and I catch on to obedience commands fast! I am crate trained, good on leash, and continue to work on other obedience skills. I am basically the whole package! 

My trainer had me out with other dogs and I did great! Due to my prey drive cats would be a no go for me. But I am great hiking on trails, playing in the lake, I absolutley love to swim, running with my buddies, and carrying my kong and ball with me. My potential family or best buddy should have GSD or working breed experience and be able to work my mind and keep me active. Older children would be best for me.

I'm neutered, current on vaccinations, heartworm negative, and microchipped. If I sound like the dog for you, then fill out an application and one of my friends at EDCGSR will contact you!

Minimum adoption donation: $350.00

If you're interested in adopting Maxx, please copy and paste this link.

animal.description:
Patty is a pint sized pittie looking for a foster or forever home.

She's sweet, sassy, and tiny, and would love an only dog home who can give her the attention she craves. She is used to being the princess, but her dad had to move into assisted living, and Patty also has special needs that was too much for everybody to keep up on, so she came back to us. 

She loves to play and get attention, she has a lot of energy and needs a constructive way to burn it all. Walks and runs are great, and she loves to play fetch in the yard. She demands attention from you if you're not giving her enough, though she does have an off button and loves to have a good cuddle on the couch. She is house trained, knows basic obedience, and is great in the car. She loves people and will crawl right into the lap of strangers!

Patty is an escape artist and needs a home with very tall, very secure fences. No chain link (she can and will climb it). She isn't a fan of other pets and wants to be the only pet. She is special needs - she has an autoimmune disease affecting her GI tract and is on a very strict diet of rx low fat food and digestive enzymes. Her body cannot process fat or protein normally, and without this diet she cannot keep on weight and everything she eats goes right through her.. We are happy to help with the expense of these things as it will be ongoing for the rest of her life. Otherwise she is happy, energetic, and ready for life!

Our volunteers love her because she is sweet, cuddly, playful, and as an attitude that makes everyone laugh. She's crate trained and well behaved, and loves her human friends so much. She's not destructive when left alone, but she is an escape artist and has been a frequent flier at animal control, so keeping her contained is a very high priority. She will steal your heart for sure, all you have to do is give her a chance!

animal.description:
Remember Mr. Twinkle, (now called Mr. T) found chained 24/7 around a pole at 2 months old with no shelter from the sun or rain in Phuket Thailand?  Based on body structure, physical and behavioral traits, it has been determined, Mr. T is a Korean Jindo mix.  While he is aloof, silly, playful, and terrible at hide & seek, you will always win, he is a typical Jindo and needs an owner who understands his breed and will take the time needed to complete training with him and build a lasting relationship with him.  Mr. T is approximately 17 months old and weighs about 40lbs.  He is a blonde/taffy colored, medium size dog that arrived in Seattle through the efforts of Tonijfortheanimals, based in Phuket Thailand, in February of 2020. There was a delay in putting him up for adoption due to the fact he was finishing up rehabilitation for knee surgery.  Then COVID-19hit, which delayed his adoption process even further. By this point he had bonded with his foster mom and he desperately needs a new fur-ever human hero to bond with and bonding takes time with this guy.  Mr. T has had 3 trial adoptions.  While he went out on his first trail adoption a very sweet, confident, playful dog, he came back with behavioral issues, scared and alpha male dominant.  He had two additional trail adoptions, but this sweet pup's behavior had been so altered, sadly, those trail adoptions were not successful. So we are pushing the reset button.  He needs a stable forever environment and a confident dog owner who will earn his trust and bond with him allowing him to feel safe.  He has been shuffled around too much, thus, the fund raising for training which will be paid directly to the trainer. 
Mr. T needs to be the only pet, currently.  That could change with training and time, but that is to be determined at a later date, after training and a new bond has been established.  He needs a home with room for him to run, a fenced yard and plenty of exercise. Typical dog outings like hiking, walks, dog park and so on are good, but he will never be suited for anyone who is a runner, due to his knee condition.  While stable and doing exceptionally well without any concerns, the constant pounding of running will not be tolerated.  If you think you can be a hero for Mr. T, please send an inquiry with a phone number, as our adoption process starts with a phone interview. 
Thanks Volunteer Staff LOVE/RESPECT/CONNECT

animal.description:
Please read full description!

Beatty is a Formosan Mountain Dog (Taiwan Dog) - which is the native/indigenous breed of Taiwan. Doing some research on this breed can help you get a better understanding of Beatty, too, though we are happy to answer questions.

For the most part, Taiwan dogs are rescued as puppies or young adults from the streets (or literally from the side of mountains) and then rehabbed and trained in Taiwan before being transferred to rescues all around the world for adoption. Some people love the breed, some don't - and that's okay! It's important to note that they generally come from long lines of feral dogs, and while they are good with people and dogs, they can be very averse to strangers. They will bark, growl, and sometimes nip, but with patience and training (and slow introductions to new people) they are great. They're generally one-person dogs, and attach themselves to one family member. They are well socialized with dogs and enjoy having canine friends.

Beatty is no exception. He is eccentric, to say the least. He barks like crazy at new people, but once he knows them he's very well behaved and seeks attention. He does nip when frustrated or excited, and while he's never had a major bite, or broken the skin, he needs to be in an adult-only home. Because he can scare strangers (and doesn't like them much anyway) he can be crated in another room while people are over to keep everybody comfortable, or a slow introduction to new people works and he can make friends. He does like other dogs and gets along extremely well with them, although he's not always in the mood to play. 

He has lived with a cat and did okay, so homes with cats can be considered. Beatty can be adopted into an only dog home or into a home with another dog of any size. What he really needs and would thrive with would be a home with adults only without a lot of visitors on a regular basis, who loves to hike, run, walk, and play in the yard. He can always use training, though he is pretty well behaved.

Our volunteers have a lot of fun with him because he is so sassy. He will tell you what he's thinking and then suddenly be sitting like the goodest boy waiting for a toy or a snack. He's a great dog, and a lot of people describe Formosans as being very "cat-like" - independent and sometimes aloof, but great dogs nonetheless. If you're looking for a dopey labrador that loves everyone and everything, he's not the right dog for you, but if you're looking for a dog with a funny personality and that would thrive with one-on-one attention or as a companion for your playful, social dog, you're looking in the right place.

Meet Mango! He’s a male Shiba Inu/Jindo mix that’s 3 year old and weighs about 62 pounds. Mango came to us as an owner surrender from a family who loved him, but couldn't give him the structure, boundaries, and rules needed for this unique breed. We often find that love is well-intended, but respect is a two way street between the dog and the human. In order to achieve balance and harmony in the house, space must be respected.

Mango has been rehabilitating with our KK9R team in NYC for the past 5 months. He possesses traits of both the Shiba and Jindo breeds: he's loyal, intelligent, happy-go-lucky, quirky, athletic, playful, and affectionate - Mango has it all! He loves being around humans and communicating with his dramatic body language! He also loves being outdoors, doing urban parkour, and running beside us on the bike.

Mango can thrive in the right forever home!  He would do best in an adult only household with no other pets. His adopter should provide a structured schedule, lots of exercise, and a respectful partnership with him. Additionally, Mango’s adopter should have previous experience with dogs and be very committed to continued training and rehabilitation.

If you're looking for a dynamic, charismatic, and bright companion for life, then Mango is the one for you! Apply to adopt Mango! 

Note: Mango’s adoption fee is $400.


———————---------------------------


INTERESTED IN ADOPTING?

Please check our Adopt page (www.koreank9rescue.org/adopt) and our Adoption FAQ (www.koreank9rescue.org/adoption-faq) to learn more! These pages include our requirements, adoption fees, adoption procedures, currently adoptable dogs, answers to frequently asked questions, and the link to our online adoption application!


NOT READY TO ADOPT BUT LOVE OUR DOGS?


As a 501(c)(3) dog rescue, we rely on donations to continue saving these precious dogs. Check our Donate page (www.koreank9rescue.org/donate) and our Patreon (www.patreon.com/koreank9rescue) to help support our rescue. Let's keep making a difference together!

Meet Daniel!

He working on trust, respect and listening. He has mastered 'sit', 'shake' and working on 'leave it'.

His ideal home would be a family with no other dogs, a fenced in backyard with no surrounding neighborhood dogs, no small children, and a passion for lazy couch potatoes!

animal.description:
"Ace" arrived at the shelter very scared, trembling with fear. He's had a tough life yet still has so much love to give. Despite what he has lived through and the anxiety he feels, he still smiles and hopes. He has waited many months for an adopter to choose him. Could you be the one? 

Ace is very high energy and needs an active home with no other dogs, no cats and children should be 14 and older. If you love the outdoors and keeping in shape, Ace is your guy. He would make a great walking/running/hiking buddy. He also enjoys car rides. Ace has boundless energy and playtime is his favorite! There's not a toy he won't fetch and it becomes a game of "try to catch me"! Once Ace tires out, he enjoys calming pets and belly rubs.

Ace knows his basic commands and is very food motivated. He has been regularly working with a trainer to improve his focus and reactivity to other dogs when out walking. Ace has made great strides and needs a committed adopter to be consistent with him. 

Ace is 5-1/2 years old, 58 lbs., neutered, current on vaccinations and completely housebroken. He has also exhibited possible separation anxiety. He has started medication to help his overall well-being and his new home should consider consulting with their vet to help Ace be his best self! 

Ace is not suited to live in an apartment/condo complex as it would be too overwhelming for him. His dream home is in a quiet area with a fenced in yard to run free and play. His ideal family will be committed to showing him what a safe, kind and stable home is. 

We kindly ask, IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS regarding Ace, PLEASE EMAIL:

 adoption@popememorialcvhs.org

How To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

animal.description:
Meet sweet Jada, a 2 year old Mastiff mix who is looking for a special someone to adopt a dog as special as she is. 

Jada had a bit of a rough start to life. After being taken in by Pet Haven, we realized she had a previously broken leg which had healed incorrectly. The good news is that she had surgery to correct it, and now the bones in her leg are all healed up. She is currently doing at home physical therapy exercises to build up her muscles in her leg, but she is walking and running like a champ. 

Jada is all about relationships and trust. Once she trusts you, oh my… she is the sweetest dog in the world. She’ll let you dremel her nails and brush her teeth with ease, is good in the bath and car, and has awesome recall. She loves to cuddle and give kisses. 

She has average to high energy, but tires out quickly. She will be your best friend. That said, she is very weary/fearful of new people (especially men) and new environments. We are working with a trainer to get her more comfortable with meeting new people. She warms up much faster to women than men. We’ll be able to give her adoptive family tips on this process. Because of her uncomfortableness with new people, she’d do best in a quieter home with fewer visitors. We are also recommending a home with dog savvy older children (15+), if any. Jada would also love a consistent routine. 

She is kennel trained, and will happily go in it for a treat. She is crated when we leave the house, and she is very quiet other than when she hears the postal carrier come. She is also potty trained, except for some submissive urination when her owners come home. As long as she’s taken outside right away, then it’s not an issue. 

She loves and lives to play! Tug and chase are her favorite games to play. She also is on the easier side to train. She knows: come, stay, sit, down, shake, go to bed, hand targeting, off, drop and heel. She is getting much better at waiting for permission to go on the couch, and for waiting for permission at the door before going outside or coming inside. She pulls slightly on a leash (we use a head halter), but it’s not bad. 

In the past, she has played with a dog and a puppy and matched their play styles. If there’s another dog in the home, it would be best if the dog was very friendly and didn’t have anxiety. Jada can be fearful and jumpy at times, so it would be nice for her to take cues from a more confident dog. The intro to another dog should be done very slowly in order to ensure success. Otherwise, she would be just fine as the only dog in the house. She has met a cat once, and tried to chase it, so she would probably do best in a house without cats. 

Because of Jada’s fearfulness, she will need a little time to transition to her new home. We are looking for someone to be patient and to give her proper time to adjust and will continue to give her the training she will need in order to be a happy dog. 






Her adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

Interested in adopting and/or learning more? Visit http://pethavenmn.org/adopt/

The neighbor had no problem hanging on to him and reached out to the rescue to help find his forever home.  

Striker loves to run and play with his dog friends and also loves to chew on a bone.  His favorite is to be his human's shadow and follow them wherever they go.  He loves going on walks and would be a great dog to take running. 

Striker would like a home where he has a 6ft fenced yard as he can jump a shorter fence.  He would do best in a home in a more rural area as loud noises scare him.  He would be an excellent companion for someone active.  

Striker is house trained. He does not do well being confined - whether it be a crate, a room, outside, or the car.  When left, his foster mom leaves him with free roam of the house and he does fine with that.  

Striker is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $100.

If you would like to adopt Striker and make him a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

4/22/2020 update - our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit. If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm LARK! I'm only about 1.5 years old and 23" at my withers.  When I arrived I was in heat so I stayed at Casa UPP until I was spayed.  Since then I've enjoyed the hospitality of a number of our favorite daycare/boarding facilities.  I do great everywhere!

I'm very enthusiastic and totally love my people.  I'm getting used to going inside and outside past the cats and don't pay much attention to them. I'm great with other dogs.  I'm might be "a little much" for a significantly older dog but really need another well-trained, well-socialized male dog in my new home to show me the ropes and keep me entertained.

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

--------

I'm FORD!  My approximate DOB is 5/15/2019.  I'm a gorgeous, tall boy.  When my rescue lady collected me from the shelter I was so scared that she had to pick me up and carry me into her car.  She tethered me in the back because she knew if she put me in a crate she'd never be able to wedge me out of there!  I promptly tried to wedge myself between the crate & side of the car (about 1.5") and stayed there for the ride "home". 

I'm still somewhat afraid of new situations so I need a family who understands this and can introduce me to new experiences slowly and calmly.  I'm very athletic and can go over fences in a heartbeat but I was having so much fun at Casa UPP I never tried it.  There was always so much to entertain me there.  I love being at daycare and am great with the pack at Casa UPP.  There are a lot of other young 'uns about my age to play with.  I'm particularly fond of Lara and Noel.  Lara showed my how much fun the pool is.

I'm OK with the cats.  I'd really like to chase them by Rescue Lady suggested that wasn't a good idea so I'm getting used to them.  I'm OK in my crate but I really prefer being on the bed with the girls.  It seems that I take up a fair amount of acreage so when she wants to go to sleep Rescue Lady frequently returns me to my crate.

From my new foster mom:  "I absolutely love to run around outside, and gallop like a dopey pony. I love to chew on sticks, toys, and bite my foster sister’s ankles when we play. I pretty much go wherever she goes. I definitely need a dog sibling. Going to the dog park is my favorite because I really get to run and meet lots of new friends. I’ve even started introducing myself to people, but I’m still a little timid if they try to pet me. Sleeping on the bed is the best thing, but I still go in my crate if I need. As long as my foster sister is around, I can be trusted out of the crate when my foster family leaves.
     I'm OK with cats and small dogs! Children intrigue me, and I like to see what they are up to but I keep my distance until I am ready and then I like to run around with them.
     I’m really a good boy and my foster family tells me I have the sweetest soul, whatever that means."

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt east of Colorado. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

Beau is a handsome 8lb, 11 year old senior gentleman.  He wasn’t taken very good care of in his younger days and is now seeking a safe, loving home to live out his golden years.  Fortunately he met a wonderful vet who contacted us to help him.  We have taken good care of him and as you can see from his photos he’s a very cool looking dude!  He does have some lasting effects of his prior life.  We had to remove all of his teeth, but he does just fine with wet food. He is house trained and does his business outside. He will however, occasionally mark inside the house. He’s not very trusting of other dogs and will lunge at them if he feels threatened.  Contrarily he is good with cats!  He has some funny quirks such as he doesn’t like being picked up with your bare hands!  It’s best to use a blanket!  He also has a thing about his face and does not like anyone getting in it!  Grooming is hard as he needs to be sedated. 
So, if you can find room in your house and heart for this little guy please let us know. He deserves to find a forever family and to know love. 
Thank you

animal.description: Two years ago Aubree was set to be euthanized around the holidays. The county shelter was packed, no one was wanting to adopt a scared, un-trusting of humans, black and white pitbull who had a fear of cars, hand touches and leashes. HARTT came across her picture on facebook and immediately stopped and said, we are going to go get her. Fast forward, Aubree grabbed the heart of all the volunteers and even was in a long term foster and was thriving. Sadly her foster had to move over seas and she had to go back into boarding. She was adopted and returned then adopted again by a more experienced owner and unfortunately, Aubree had to be returned because she was acting different. We too noticed something was off, so we evaluated her and noticed she was depressed, not acting like her self. Blood work was done and found out she has hypothyroidism, manageable with medication she takes twice a day and a different simple diet. She is now thriving and doing well, going for walks in the morning, meeting new people and playing with toys again. Aubree would do best in a calm house hold who will help continue to build her confidence and shower her with love. She does take a few times to trust and she is protective over her family so we are looking for a low key calm home who understands her breed and would continue to build her confidence with positive enforcement and treats! SHE LOVES TREATS Aubree is spayed, vaccinated, chipped, and comes with a bunch of new home goodies for her future home. She is sponsored  by one of our volunteers that agreed to pay her adoption fee for whichever home Aubree chooses. Interested in adopting Aubree, contact Destiny@azhartt.org

animal.description:
This is Juno, 
He is one of our project dogs who was rescued in the summer of 2019 from the rural area. He was skinny, dirty and starving, covered in mud and no one was caring for him. After a Good Samaritan reached out to HARTT in hopes we could help get this scared boy, we immediately jumped on the case and safely rescued him. Juno has a long way to come, he is scared but sweet. He loves the companion ship of other dogs just doesn't know how to be a, "dog". 
He isn't ready for walks or a busy house hold but if you have a calm home, calm, social dogs and willing to work with Juno, he would grow so much in a consistent house hold. 
Juno is about 3-4 years old, neutered, vaccinated and chipped. 

Juno is currently in our rehabilitation program at our foster home where the foster is continuing working with him and a few of our other project dogs till they find the right family who can continue working with them to build their confidence and be forever home. 

If you are interested in Juno, please reach out to adopt@azhartt.org for more information about Juno and our foster rehabilitation program.

animal.description:
This is a courtesy post for a senior GSD, Rachel, who is looking for a new family.

 

“I was born on July 23, 2013. When I was a little puppy I got out and got hit by a car. My owner couldn’t care for me. I was doomed to a kill shelter in Apple Valley, California. But a man named Brian rescued me. He runs the “Puppy Coalition Rescue” in San Marcos, CA. He got my injured hip and leg ?xed via surgery and trained me to be a companion to an elderly woman who recently passed. She left me as part of her estate to her family, but they are not dog people…so they surrendered me to a local trainer to help find me a home.

On January 8th, 2020 two cool humans, Shayne and Susan, founders of the “GNAW ON THEIR SKULL ACADEMY” (GOTS), ?gured out that I was unhappy, irritable & overweight. I was 102Lbs, and not exercised. I was allergic to the food I was being fed. I was a mess. Not anymore. “Look at Me Now!” I’m a lean 69lbs. I love people, dogs, and kids. I just bark a little…”

The best fit for Rachel will be a family with GSD experience, and an understanding of her medical needs (Allergies). She is a wonderful companion and can be placed in a home as an only dog, or with other dogs. She also is cat friendly!

If you are interested in Adopting Rachel or would like more information on her, please contact Shayne at 619.559.0222, or via email at shayneganz@me.com.
Please visit http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/ to learn more about our dogs. Click on available dogs to see further descriptions. If you are interested in me, please contact us at information@coastalgsrsd.org or call (858) 779-9149. Don't forget to fill out our online application:  http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/webform/1774/adoption-application.

The minimum adoption donation ranges from $300 to $400. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100% tax deductible.

Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

animal.description:
Appa followed his fosters home one night, after having wandered around the neighborhood. He was overheated, thirsty, hungry and exhausted. His body was covered in lacerations and his feet were red and sore from the hot pavement. He slept for days before feeling energetic enough to act like a normal dog.

Here are some facts about Appa:
 
-He’s a very sociable dog, loves lots of pets and snuggles, but he isn’t against having some alone time.
-He’s happy to lounge around the house, and typically appreciates sleeping in. Once he’s up, he can enjoy higher energy activities like jogging or hiking. 
-Whether you are strolling along or running, Appa is okay with sticking to your pace, as long as there’s nothing exciting around, like other dogs, and small animals, which really excite him.
-Appa is comfortable sharing his food and toys and has never shown aggression towards humans.
-Appa is gentle about taking treats and knows how to sit before getting his meals.
-Appa would be a great companion for a variety of high energy, dog-loving homes. Do you think you’d be a good fit for this sweet, affectionate boy? Contact us to meet Appa today!

animal.description:
Meet Freckles
Sweet, handsome, roly poly Freckles is just a big love bug who’s led a very scary life before coming to our shelter. We rescued Freckles from a high-kill shelter. He arrived on June 18, 2020. We’re glad he’s here in our safety and care. Freckles was so scared and shut down that in an over-crowded shelter like the one he came from, he could have been one of the first to go down because he was too scared to make human connection… until he learned he could trust you.
Freckles is thought to be an American Bulldog mix. He’s two years old and weighs 67 lbs. He’s mostly all white with the cutest brown patches that cover his ears, sort of like he’s wearing a hat. He wears the sweetest expression and his eyes hold a lot of innocence and expectation. He’s absolutely adorable, like a big teddy bear. 
Since arriving, Freckles has been smothered with positive attention and kindness and he’s responding beautifully. Every day he’s learning that not all hands hit and that having a safe place to sleep at night and plenty of food does wonders for the soul. Freckles is learning to trust. Once he knows that you’re not going to hurt him, Freckles loves to give doggie kisses and tail wags. He loves being with people. One of his favorite things to do is sit with his person and be petted.  
Freckles does best with a gentle approach. Sudden movements, especially over his head, loud barking and fire sirens scare him and he shuts down. He’s not aggressive in any way, but he withdraws and moves away hoping that he won’t get hurt. It’s quite heartbreaking to see him this way, but with quiet encouragement and patient assurance, Freckles will engage when he thinks things are okay. When he does, we’re able to see the big overgrown puppy that Freckles wants to be. 
Freckles walks very well on a leash. He loves his walks. A fenced yard is a must for Freckles. Given his past, if he’s bored or gets frightened, he’ll dig furiously as if he’s trying to get away. What a terrible life this beautiful boy must have led, but we are so happy he’s adjusting every day and is able to let go of the baggage that is his past. We haven’t yet tested Freckles with other dogs, but we do know that he’s terribly afraid of cats and may do best in a home without them.
Freckles is a wonderful dog. With a kind and patient person, Freckles will blossom under their attention and consistency. Freckles is showing us every day the dog he wants to be - carefree, fun loving, and affectionate. He has so much love and loyalty just waiting to give to his person. He truly just wants to belong to someone who won’t hurt him, but will show him what a loving life can be. Perhaps you’ll be the one to give Freckles his chance at a happy life. 
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. 75N, Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
Meet Bubba Joe! Bubba Joe is just over a year old. He was found as a stray with all 4 of his K9’s filed down. Sadly that is usually one of the signs of a dog that is going to live a life of breeding. Luckily for him he escaped the life that was being planned out for him and will never be subjected to be used and abused. 

Bubba Joe is a perfectly sweet gentleman. He loves all the dogs in his foster home and loves to play in the fenced in yard. He has no reaction to any dogs that bark at him or try to be overly dominant. He just wants to be everyone’s best friend. Given his age he would do best in an active home. He would love a family who likes to hike, walk or play in the yard. He would be fine with kids. Cats unknown (he can be cat tested for potential adopters). 

Bubba Joe is fully vetted- up to date on all shots, neutered and micro-chipped. He is heartworm negative. He is also current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention. He is available for meet and greets. He can also be adopted out of state to approved adopters- a transport fee would apply in addition to his adoption fee.

animal.description:
Buster loves to snuggle and sleeps under covers with his foster. He gets along with all 6 of his foster's other dogs and 4 dog-savvy cats. He is very curious about the cats, but does not chase them and is not mean to them. We've included several pictures of Buster interacting with other dogs. Buster is the apricot colored Chihuahua mix pictured in the first picture. 

However, Buster recently came from a very bad situation, so he still needs lots of work learning where to potty.

Buster also still needs lots of people socialization, and a home that will understand that it may take him a couple of weeks to warm up to people. Due to coming from a terrible situation, he is very hand shy, as though he expects to be hit, and he does growl and become very bitey when he is scared. Right now, he is particularly scared of having his nails clipped. He's working very hard to be less scared and bitey. Buster needs to find a home with no small children. 

But when he has chosen you to love, Buster can't get close enough to you and will wrap himself around your neck. He likes to be the center of attention, and can get jealous of other animals when he is getting petted.

Meet Woody! He is about 2-3 years old, and a Chihuahua mix. Woody has been through alot. Woody was the victim of a terrible hoarding situation where he was housed in filthy conditions with over 30 other dogs. They were lucky if they ever got a meal, and never shown any love. Woody was extremely terrified and did not know what human contact was. This little cutie has come a long way since he arrived at Paw Parent. 

We have been working with Woody, he has came very far but still needs a little more time and love. He now knows what love is and has bonded with one of our crew. He follows her everywhere, and is just happy as can be. Woody is ready for a loving home that would be willing to work with him and pull him out of his shell. This little guy has lots of love to give!

Woody does need a calm environment as he gets scared very easily. He is still very timid, but really wants to bond and be loved. He does need someone who is extremely patient and willing to give him the time he needs. 

Woody is neutered, chipped and up to date on all routine vaccinations. If you would like more information on Woody or if you would like to meet him please contact us 661-724-0642 pawparent@gmail.com

Please note that while we are closed to the public we will not be responding to pet inquiries. Once animals are posted, we immediately begin receiving adoption applications. Adoption appointments are scheduled first come, first served. (See our adoption procedures below.)

Freeway will be your best friend once you spend some time with her. She came to the shelter after being found as a stray running alongside a busy freeway. Freeway really loves taking car rides and going on walks/jogs. Her favorite volunteer has been taking her to Wildwood Park on the weekends, and she loves these little adventures. Freeway loves all people but would do best with adults and older children. She can be a bit picky about her canine friends and seems to do best with male dogs. If you think you might be that special person Freeway has been waiting for, please visit warmhearts.org to complete our adoption application. Freeway's estimated DOB is 1/1/2012; she weighs approx 43 lbs.

Freeway was generously sponsored by Renee Shapiro during our virtual Reigning Cats and Dogs event. Thank you Renee for sponsoring Freeway!

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

animal.description:
Adoption Fee:  $100
Fostered in Baton Rouge, Louisiana
Age: 12.5 years
Weight: 6.4 lbs.

7/26/20 - Hey everyone.  It’s Milo the Magnificent!  Yep, that’s how I feel now.  No longer in a field having to fend for myself, no longer in a home where they don’t want me, no longer just Milo… MILO THE MAGNIFICENT!!  I know this sounds as if I know some magic tricks, and I actually do.  You see, I’m blind, but everywhere I go, I adjust very quickly and seem to learn my way around without fail.  I do lightly bump into things, but I’m not timid or scared of my shortcoming which makes me all the more magnificent.  I haven’t been blind all my life, but I will be 13 years old in December, so there were bound to be some body parts that started to give up.  I’m just glad it wasn’t my bladder. Haha.  Yes, a magician AND a comic.  Two dogs for the price of one. 

So, my upkeep, since I have KCS, which is actually a fancy term for dry-eye, I get Optimmune ointment, 1 strip in each eye twice daily.  I also get artificial eye drops in my eyes a couple times a day. 

I’m fine with the other fur-beings in the house as long as they don’t get too much up in my business.  Being blind does keep you on higher alert.  I don’t like to sleep in the human bed since I’m afraid I might fall.  I’m very content in a very comfy doggy bed with a blanket.  Foster mom feeds us twice daily.  This is when I do my best magic.  She puts my bowl with soft food down and I empty the bowl.  Not all dogs are this good, I know.

I get along with all people and will LOVE anyone who holds me.  I absolutely LOVE to be held like a baby over your shoulder.  I could stay there all day.  I am pretty free with my kisses too.  I don’t play with toys, but you never know later on.

Even though I cannot see, I’m pretty good with my potty habits if you do your job and take me out often.  Once I get comfortable, I will even get out of my bed and bark and when foster mom brings me out, I tinkle. 

I like to walk around outside, but not sure if a fenced in yard is totally necessary if you are sure you stay out with me the whole time.  Then again, who would put a dog out and let it stay out alone to use the bathroom with all the hawks and wild animals around.  That’s not the type owner I want next.  Not sure that apartment or condo life would be for me since I do have a bark and am not afraid to use it.

That’s all I have to say about myself for now.  If you would like to help me take this magician act on the road, just fill out an application and my new employees will see if you can cut the mustard.

Signing off for now.  POOF!

7/2/20 - Milo had his dental yesterday.  He lost 7 teeth that were just aching to come out.  His tummy was a little upset last night and he wasn't feeling all that great, but today is a new day.  And, it is the first day of the rest of his great life.  Rotten teeth and bacteria free now, and still eating like a champ.  Milo eats soft food and cleans his plate.  For his eyes, he gets Optimmune ointment, 1 strip in each eye twice daily to help with the KCS/dry eyes.  He also gets Neopolydex, 1 drop in each eye twice daily for inflammation and the infection in his eyes.  We will be following up with the ophthalmologist later to get the long-term regime for this sweeties little eyes.

Being blind is not something that holds Milo back.  Some dogs just adjust well, and he is one of them.  We think Milo was an agility dog in his previous life.  How else could you explain the way he just flies over all the hurdles that have been put in his path?  Well, that and he must have angels riding on his back.  

6/25/20 - Milo is 13 years old, blind and was found lost in a field near Arlington, TX and turned into Mansfield Shelter.  Milo had a chip and his owners were contacted.  They informed that he had gone missing a few months back and they could not find him.  The owner had since gotten a new job and was working long hours and said that getting Milo back would not be in Milo’s best interest, so agreed to surrender him to Yorkie Haven Rescue since the shelter had already reached out us.  He was pulled from the shelter Monday, June 22nd and transported to a layover home in Shreveport.  We brought him to the vet since his eyes were very infected.  He has very mature cataracts and had bilateral conjunctivitis with mucoid discharge.  He also has KCS (dry eye) so will be on medicated ointment from now on.  Saturday, June 27th, Milo will complete his transport to his foster home in Baton Rouge.  Once he is comfortable, we will get him to the vet to get blood work done, along with a much needed dental and we are sure he will lose infected teeth.  Even with his rough journey lately, being blind and changing multiple hands, and not know what was going on and who to trust, Milo has been a champ through it all.  He does love to be attended to and talked to.

The bad pictures are of Milo when he was first brought to the shelter after being on his own.  The cuter one is, of course, after the shelter trimmed and bathed him.  Once we get him in his permanent foster home, he will get to visit the professional groomer and photographer and we will show you just what a handsome boy Milo can be.  Basically, all dogs ask for in life is food, grooming, vetting and love.  We don’t feel this is too much to ask for from a companion that never asked to be brought into this world but was purchased as a young pup to give a human.  Then, WHAM, when they need us the most, …….. the humans cannot give that in return.  That is where rescue comes in.  Seems we can pick forever homes MUCH BETTER than the breeders who sell them in the beginning.  Harsh, I think not!  Proven!

Milo will be letting you know more about his personality, needs and wants as we get to know him better.  Stay tuned!

animal.description:
Branton is a 2 year old border collie. He is such a handsome boy! Branton has lived most of his life with dogs and is now learning to trust people. He is very skittish and his current safe place is his crate. Because of this, potential adopters will have multiple meet and greets in order for us to identify his ideal home. Branton cannot walk on a leash and because of his fear of people, is considered a flight risk. His ideal family would offer a home with a fenced yard and a family that is willing to spend many hours working on building his trust. Stability and a routine are critical. Branton will allow you to touch him, pet him, and love on him.... It's truly going to be a labor of love. We are working with this precious boy and look forward to seeing his happily ever after fairytale ending! If you are interested in learning more about Branton, please apply to
angelsrescue.org
.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Brent came from a hoarding case in Suwannee County. Due to poor living conditions and neglect, Brent suffered from a skin condition known as demodex mange. His fur has since grown back, and he's been learning to live and breathe easy. As a remnant of the abuse he can be standoffish and distrusting at first, but once he gets to know you, a funny and loving dog emerges. He takes longer to get used to men than women and will need patience and persistence to build your trust. He thinks he is a lap dog and will do all he can to get your attention. While humans sometimes scare him, he has lived with dogs of all sizes from 15 to 95 lbs and is quick to instigate play time! He'll do great in a home with an energetic and playful dog that is ideally his size or larger. He is very energetic and loves playing with other dogs! Brent has been working with a trainer to get used to meeting new people in public. He has made a lot of progress, but will need plenty more positive experiences and interactions to be completely comfortable. He is very food oriented without getting defensive, which has made for great encouragement in his progress. Because he is so food motivated, he is highly trainable. Brent is very smart and knows how to sit, lay down, and shake on command. Brent loves his crate, is housebroken, and is very confident on leash. If you are up for an extremely rewarding challenge, Brent is the dog for you. 
Requirements: Fenced backyard, no kids, no cats, another active dog in the home.

Please visit our website at faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets if you are interested in adopting.

I am a mixed breed dog. This means I don't have a specific recognizable breed. The rescue uses the following guide which are guesses based on my current size and age for how big I will be when full grown: Mixed Breed (small) up to 25 pounds - Mixed Breed (medium) between 25-45 pounds - Mixed Breed (large) more than 50 pounds. For more information on, please visit the website https://faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets.

We are setting up adoptions with approved adopters on an appointment basis. We are no longer hosting adoption events at PetSmart until further notice. We are not arranging meet and greets; but appointments to finalize adoptions to limit exposure for all. Our adoptions come with a one week trial period in which if things are not working out, we will refund your adoption fee if you decide to return your newly adopted Faithful Friend. Our adoptions must be done in person and we do not arrange transport to adopters. Our adoption fees vary and we are only able to accept payments by card* at this time but include spay/neuter, heartworm test (dogs), FeLV/FIV test (cats), age appropriate vaccines and deworming, flea, tick and heartworm medication and microchip. Dog/puppy adoption fees range from $150-$400. Cat/kitten adoption fees range from $50-$150.

animal.description: From Foster Lori - We are temporarily fostering a stray brought to us Nov 2019 and need help to get him adopted into a furever home. Ranger is fully vaccinated, neutered, has microchip and heartworm negative. Please contact Ranger's foster family to meet him and get adoption info: Lori 404-376-3776. Looking for love at first sight? You found him! Meet your new best friend! Ranger will love you unconditionally, provide constant companionship and LOTS of snuggling. Ranger LOVES people and is eager to meet everyone, bounding up with a big smile, begging to be pet. Then he'll happily melt at your feet. Ranger is energetic, dog-friendly and likes playing, chasing and clowning around with other dogs in the yard, as well as cuddling up and napping with them. Ranger would enjoy a multi dog family with a fenced yard to play and sunbathe. But, as YOUR best friend, Ranger prefers to spend most of his time by your side throughout the day, as you cook, clean, or binge TV on the couch. Ranger is an attentive listener, intuitive to your feelings, caring, and offers empathetic snuggles. Ranger is an adult (4 yo+) neutered male pit bull terrier mix, 60 lbs, brown with white neck, feet and snout. Ranger was found as a stray in awful condition suffering from separation anxiety and skin allergies; but he is SO resilient! Strong, healthy, velvety soft and full of love! Ranger is ready for his new best friend to bring him home where he will feel safe and loved at last. Please contact Ranger's foster family to meet him and get adoption info: Lori 404-376-3776

animal.description: Scully IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Scully, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=22292&name=ScullyScully is a laid back, easy going guy who would love to have a best friend with whom to spend his retirement years. He's an active senior, around 9 years old, who absolutely adores going for walks and doesn't need any assistance, thank you very much. He is happy to walk for over a mile and then will celebrate by taking a nap when he gets home. He's a napping professional and can often be found on his back, looking like he fell asleep mid-rollover. While Scully gets along with everyone, he doesn't like to be touched when he doesn't see it coming. Because of this, we think a home with no children would be best. He's in a foster home with two young adults and he has proven to be a great house guest who is potty trained, good in the house, and easy on a leash.The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is tax deductible. The adoption donation provides that all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis ( i.e., puppies who will need to be altered by 6 mos old). Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.
